{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181019033913|864735273","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Thomas_Suozzi","to":"Thomas Suozzi"}],"pages":{"1846883":{"pageid":1846883,"ns":0,"title":"Thomas Suozzi","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-20T18:47:30Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Thomas Suozzi\n|image        = Thomas Suozzi official photo.jpg\n|state        = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|district     = {{ushr|NY|3|3rd}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2017\n|term_end     =\n|predecessor  = [[Steve Israel]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[County Executive|Executive]] of [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau County]]\n|term_start1  = January 1, 2002\n|term_end1    = December 31, 2009\n|predecessor1 = [[Thomas Gulotta]]\n|successor1   = [[Ed Mangano]]\n|office2      = Mayor of [[Glen Cove, New York|Glen Cove]]\n|term_start2  = January 1, 1994\n|term_end2    = December 31, 2001\n|predecessor2 = Donald DeRiggi\n|successor2   = [[Mary Ann Holzkamp]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1962|8|31}}\n|birth_place  = [[Glen Cove, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = Helene Suozzi\n|children     = 3\n|education    = [[Boston College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Fordham University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website      = {{url|suozzi.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Thomas R. Suozzi'''  ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|w|\u0252|z|i}}; born August 31, 1962) is an American [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] politician, CPA and attorney who is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[New York's 3rd congressional district|New York's 3rd district]].<ref name=Suozzihousewin>{{cite web|title=Suozzi defeats Martins in 3rd District race |url=http://longisland.news12.com/news/suozzi-declares-victory-over-martins-in-3rd-district-race-1.12585491|website=longisland.news12.com|accessdate=November 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Suozzibio>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=https://suozzi.house.gov/about/biography|website=suozzi.house.gov|accessdate=November 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was the [[County Executive]] of [[Nassau County, New York]], in office from 2002 to 2009. He was first elected to the post in 2001 after four terms as mayor of [[Glen Cove, New York]]. In 2006, he ran unsuccessfully against [[Eliot Spitzer]] for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nomination for [[List of Governors of New York|Governor of New York]]. Suozzi was narrowly defeated for re-election in 2009 by [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee [[Ed Mangano]], and in a rematch in 2013 was again defeated, this time by a much larger margin of 59% to 41%.<ref name=\"Twarowski\">{{cite news|last=Twarowski|first=Christopher|date=November 6, 2013|title=Mangano Defeats Suozzi In Nassau County Executive Race |url=https://www.longislandpress.com/2013/11/06/mangano-defeats-suozzi-in-nassau-county-executive-race|newspaper=Long Island Press|location=Syosset, NY}}</ref>\n\nSuozzi sits on the House Foreign Affairs Committee and the House Armed Services Committee. He is Vice-Chair of the Bipartisan Problem Solvers Caucus, which consists of 22 Democrats and 22 Republican working together to find solutions. He is also the Co-Chair of the Long Island Sound Caucus and Co-Chair of the Quiet Skies Caucus.<ref name=\"Suozzibio\"/><ref name=pressrelease>{{cite web|title=Suozzi appointed co chair of bipartisan long island sound caucus|url= https://suozzi.house.gov/media/press-releases/suozzi-appointed-co-chair-bipartisan-long-island-sound-caucus|website=suozzi.house.gov|accessdate=November 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early and personal life==\nThe son of former [[Glen Cove, New York|Glen Cove]] mayor [[Joseph A. Suozzi]], Thomas Suozzi was born on August 31, 1962 in [[Glen Cove, New York|Glen Cove]].<ref>Rodrick, Stephen. [http://nymag.com/news/politics/17665/index3.html \"Tom Quixote\"], ''[[New York Magazine]]''.</ref> His father, Joseph, was born in Italy and his mother, Marguerite, is of Irish and English descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/newsday-interviews-thomas-suozzi-i-m-pretty-much-a-go-go-guy-1.791436 |title=INTERVIEWS THOMAS SUOZZI / 'I'm pretty much a go-go guy.' |publisher=Newsday |date=2001-09-05 |accessdate=2016-12-18}}</ref> The youngest of five siblings, Tom Suozzi attended Catholic schools, graduating from [[Chaminade High School]], [[Boston College]], and [[Fordham University School of Law]]. Suozzi and his wife, Helene, have three children.\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Mayor of Glen Cove===\nIn 1993, Suozzi was elected mayor of [[Glen Cove, New York]]. He was in that municipality's mayoral office for four terms.<ref name=governing>{{cite news|last1=Gurwitt|first1=Rob|title=Thomas R. Suozzi |url=http://www.governing.com/poy/Thomas-Suozzi.html|accessdate=August 1, 2016|publisher=Governing Magazine|date=2005}}</ref>\n\nHis father and his uncle, Vincent Suozzi, respectively, were mayors of Glen Cove prior to Tom Suozzi.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Toy|first1=Vivian|title=In Glen Cove, Politics Is Thicker Than Blood |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F00E1DC133EF932A1575BC0A9639C8B63|accessdate=1 August 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=August 21, 2005}}</ref>\n\nAs mayor, Suozzi focused on environmental cleanup of commercial and industrial sites in Glen Cove. A focal point of his administration was redeveloping brownfield and [[superfund]] sites.<ref name=governing/> In 1994, the Glen Cove incinerator was permanently closed and dismantled.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ain|first1=Stewart|title=First Closing Of Incinerator Renews Focus On Disposing Of Garbage|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/03/24/nyregion/first-closing-of-incinerator-renews-focus-on-disposing-of-garbage.html|accessdate=October 25, 2016|publisher=New York Times |date=March 24, 1996}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, the city demolished and redeveloped the defunct Li Tungsten Refinery grounds, a federal superfund site.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Saslow|first1=Linda|title=Glen Cove Seeks Waterfront Investors |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/11/05/nyregion/glen-cove-seeks-waterfront-investors.html|accessdate=October 25, 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=November 5, 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gearty|first1=Robert|title=Glen Cove Blows Its Stack|url= http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/boroughs/glen-cove-blows-stack-article-1.800385|accessdate=October 25, 2016 |publisher=New York Daily News|date=April 23, 1998}}</ref>\n\nHe was recognized by then-Vice President [[Al Gore]] for the city's environmental cleanup efforts and Glen Cove was awarded the Brownfields Award in 1998.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tedeschi |first1=Tony|title=The Glen Cove Waterfront Sound Off|url=http://patch.com/new-york/glencove/the-glen-cove-waterfront-sound-off|accessdate=October 25, 2016|publisher=Patch|date=July 22, 2010}}</ref><ref name=newsdaysecondchance>{{cite news|last1=Brodsky|first1=Robert|title=Thomas Suozzi Pushes For Second Chance In Nassau County Executive Race |url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/nassau/thomas-suozzi-pushes-for-second-chance-in-nassau-county-executive-race-1.6350690|accessdate=26 October 2016 |publisher=Newsday |date=October 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Nassau County Executive===\nSuozzi was elected [[Nassau County, New York|Nassau County]] Executive in 2001, becoming the first Democrat elected to the position in traditionally Republican Nassau in 30 years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lambert|first1=Bruce|title=The 2001 Elections: Long Island; Suozzi Quickly Focuses on Nassau's Woes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/08/nyregion/the-2001-elections-long-island-suozzi-quickly-focuses-on-nassau-s-woes.html?_r=0|accessdate=October 27, 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=November 8, 2001}}</ref> He assumed office in the midst of a fiscal crisis. By 1999, Nassau was on the brink of financial collapse: the county faced a $300 million annual deficit, was billions of dollars in debt, and its credit rating had sunk to one level above junk status.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Bart|title=Nassau's Finances Recall Near-Meltdown of '99|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/nassau/nassau-s-finances-recall-near-meltdown-of-99-1.2554155 |accessdate=November 2, 2016|publisher=Newsday|date=December 19, 2010}}</ref> According to ''The New York Times'', he \"earned high marks from independent institutions for his signature achievement, the resuscitation of Nassau's finances.\"<ref name=Suozzinumbers>{{cite news|last1=Lambert|first1=Bruce|title=Suozzi, Beyond the Numbers |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/04/nyregion/suozzi-beyond-the-numbers.html|accessdate=November 2, 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=September 4, 2006}}</ref>\n\nWhile in office, Suozzi cut spending and reduced borrowing and debt. He also oversaw 11 county bond upgrades over the course of two years, eliminated deficits in Nassau, and accumulated surpluses. In 2005, ''[[Governing Magazine]]'' named Suozzi one of its Public Officials of the Year, calling him \"the man who spearheaded Nassau County, New York's, remarkable turnaround from the brink of fiscal disaster.\"<ref name=governing/><ref name=Suozzinumbers/> According to ''The New York Times'', Suozzi garnered praise for social services like his \"no wrong door\" program, which centralized access to social services.<ref name=Suozzinumbers/>\n\nIn 2004, Georgina Morgenstern, a former Nassau County planning department employee, alleged Suozzi and Chief Deputy County Executive Anthony Cancellieri used county employees, resources and functions for illegal fundraising. Morgenstern said she was retaliated against and terminated without due process, and she subsequently filed a multimillion-dollar lawsuit.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Twarowski|first1=Christopher|title=Skeletons In The Closet|url=http://www.longislandpress.com/2009/08/06/skeletons-in-the-closet|accessdate=August 1, 2016|publisher=Long Island Press|date=August 6, 2009|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090816205603/http://www.longislandpress.com/2009/08/06/skeletons-in-the-closet|archivedate=August 16, 2009|df=}}</ref> Suozzi was dismissed from the case and a federal jury in Central Islip rejected Morgenstern's claim that she was fired in retaliation for her criticism of Suozzi.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Murphy|first1=William|title=Nassau Lawsuit Ends With $4M Whimper|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle/nassau-lawsuit-ends-with-4m-whimper-1.1993123|accessdate=November 4, 2016|publisher=Newsday|date=June 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2006 gubernatorial campaign===\nSuozzi declared that he was running for [[Governor of New York]] in the Democratic primary against [[Eliot Spitzer]] on February 25, 2006. The bid appeared from the start to be somewhat of a long shot given Spitzer's reputation as a \"corporate crusader\", though Suozzi often pointed out that he prevailed as a long shot before when he first ran for Nassau County Executive.\n\nFew prominent Democrats outside of Nassau County Democratic Party Chairman Jay Jacobs supported his bid; most of New York's Democratic legislators and mayors campaigned with Spitzer. One of his biggest supporters was Victor Rodriguez, founder of the now disbanded Voter Rights Party. Rodriguez eventually became the lead field organizer for the Albany campaign office. The campaign was funded in part by [[Home Depot]] co-founder [[Kenneth Langone]], former NYSE CEO [[Richard Grasso]], [[David S. Mack|David Mack]] of the MTA, and many individuals on [[Wall Street]] who had been investigated and prosecuted by Eliot Spitzer.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rodrick|first1=Stephen|title=Tom Quixote: Is Suozzi's campaign against Spitzer a profile in courage or self-destruction?|url=http://nymag.com/news/politics/17665|accessdate=August 1, 2016|publisher=New York Magazine}}</ref>\n\nOn June 13, 2006, Suozzi spoke before the New York State Conference of Mayors along with Spitzer and [[John Faso]]. Suozzi received a standing ovation by the crowd of mayors.<ref>{{cite news |first=Danny|last=Hakim|title=Suozzi Gets an Ovation From Conference of Mayors|date=June 14, 2006|publisher=New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/14/nyregion/14gov.html}}</ref> On July 6, 2006, Suozzi announced to his followers that he had collected enough petitions to place himself on the ballot in the primary against Spitzer. He claimed victory to the press in the debate on July 25, 2006 with [[New York State Attorney General]] Eliot Spitzer held at [[Pace University]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}  He stated he had presidential aspirations during the course of this debate.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Healy|first1=Patrick|title=Sole Debate for Spitzer and Suozzi Is Fiery |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/26/nyregion/26gov.html |accessdate=November 4, 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=July 26, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C07E1DF123FF935A15754C0A9609C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=1|work=The New York Times|title=The Spitzer-Suozzi Debate Transcript |date=July 26, 2006|accessdate=May 25, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn August 7, 2006, Suozzi announced after much speculation that he would not seek an independent line were he to lose the primary to Spitzer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suozzi Won't Seek Independent Line|date=August 7, 2006|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|url=http://publicbroadcasting.net/wned/news.newsmain?action=article&ARTICLE_ID=951416&sectionID=1}}</ref>\n\n===2009 Nassau County executive election===\nSuozzi lost the 2009 county executive election to Ed Mangano.\n\n===2013 Nassau County executive election===\nAfter first working in the private sector as an attorney, Suozzi announced that he would seek a rematch against Mangano in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suozzi lays out campaign strategy, six months out|url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle-1.812042/suozzi-lays-out-campaign-strategy-six-months-out-1.5216532|publisher=Newsday|date=May 7, 2013|accessdate=May 21, 2013}}</ref> He attacked Mangano for \"presiding over a decline in the county\", while also emphasizing that, while he was County Executive, Suozzi had eight years of balanced budgets and reduced crime.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Nassau County Executive Tom Suozzi Wants His Old Job Back: Says He's Over Losing The First Time And Is What's Right For County This Time |url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2013/02/13/former-nassau-county-executive-tom-suozzi-wants-his-old-job-back|publisher=CBS New York|date=February 13, 2013|accessdate=May 21, 2013}}</ref> In November, Mangano easily defeated Suozzi, 59 percent to 41.<ref name=\"Twarowski\"/>\n\n===2016 U.S. House campaign===\nIn June 2016, Suozzi won a five-way Democratic primary in [[New York's 3rd congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brand|first1=Rick|title=Thomas Suozzi savors Democratic primary win |url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/thomas-suozzi-savors-democratic-primary-win-1.11986382|website=Newsday.com|publisher=Newsday|accessdate=July 9, 2016}}</ref> Suozzi received endorsements from ''The New York Times'', ''Newsday'', and ''The Island Now''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Editorial Board|first1=The New York Times|title=Five Choices in New York Congressional Primaries|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/18/opinion/five-choices-in-new-york-congressional-primaries.html|accessdate=November 4, 2016|publisher=New York Times|date=June 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Editorial Board|first1=Newsday|title=Thomas Suozzi to Represent 3rd Congressional District|url=http://www.newsday.com/opinion/editorial/elect-thomas-suozzi-in-3rd-congressional-district-1.12499930|accessdate=November 4, 2016|publisher=Newsday|date=October 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Editorial Board|first1=The Island Now|title=Our Views: Congressional District 3 Tom Suozzi For Congress|url=http://www.theislandnow.com/opinions/our-views-congressional-district-tom-suozzi-for-congress/article_8f9e797a-a1d1-11e6-a3bd-8f3ebf164084.html|accessdate=November 4, 2016|publisher=The Island Now|date=November 3, 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104151805/http://www.theislandnow.com/opinions/our-views-congressional-district-tom-suozzi-for-congress/article_8f9e797a-a1d1-11e6-a3bd-8f3ebf164084.html|archivedate=November 4, 2016|df=}}</ref> He defeated Republican [[Jack Martins]] in the general election on November 8, 2016, and began representing [[New York's 3rd congressional district]] in the [[115th United States Congress]] in January 2017.<ref name=Suozzihousewin/>\n\n===2018 U.S. House campaign===\n\nSuozzi is a member of the [[Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://capac-chu.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus|date=|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref> the [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> and the [[Climate Solutions Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=90 Current Climate Solutions Caucus Members|author=|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus/|format=|publisher=Citizen\u00b4s Climate Lobby |date=|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{| border=1 cellpadding=4 cellspacing=0 style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\"\n! colspan=5|Nassau County Executive Race\n|- style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\"\n! Year\n! Candidate\n! style=\"width: 50px\"|Votes\n! style=\"width: 40px\"|%\n|-\n| rowspan = 2 | 2009\n|| Thomas Suozzi ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 117,874\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 48%\n|-\n|| Ed Mangano ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 118,111\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 49%\n|}\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |New York 3rd Congressional District Race\n|- style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\"\n! Year\n! Candidate\n! style=\"width: 50px\" |Votes\n! style=\"width: 40px\" |%\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2016\n|| Thomas Suozzi ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 156,315\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 52.4%\n|-\n|| [[Jack Martins]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 142,023\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 47.6%\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[New York gubernatorial election, 2006]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://suozzi.house.gov/ Congressman Thomas Suozzi] official U.S. House website\n* [http://suozziforcongress.com/ Campaign website]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/New_York/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Thomas_Suozzi_%5BD-3%5D}}\n* {{ CongLinks | congbio = S001201 | fec = H6NY03247 | votesmart = 92111 | congress = thomas-suozzi/S001201}}\n* {{C-SPAN|tomsuozzi}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Donald DeRiggi]]| tit